The economic efficiency indices, e.g., total revenue (TR), net profit (NP), income equivalent ratios (IER), maize equivalent yield (MEY), monetary advantage index (MAI), relative value total (RVT), and replacement value of intercropping (RVI) were calculated to assess the economic feasibility of maize-soybean intercropping patterns integrated with mineral-NNPs fertilization. The TR was computed by considering the economic yields (e.g., grain and seed for maize and soybean, respectively) based on prevailing market prices of agricultural inputs, human labor, and returns during the 2019 and 2020 seasons in U.S. dollars (US$). All monetary values were converted to US$ according to the average local official exchange price, which amounted to 17.87 and 17.88 Egyptian pounds for each US$ 1 in the 2019 and 2020 seasons, respectively. Output prices were US$ 199.86 and 199.74 tâ1 for maize grains and US$ 447.68 and 447.43 tâ1 for soybean seeds in the 2019 and 2020 seasons, respectively. The TR (US$ haâ1)â=âmonetary value of maize grainsâ+âmonetary value of soybean seeds. The NP (US$ haâ1)â=â[(YâÃâP) â VPC], where Y is the economic yield (grain or seed) in t haâ1, P is the yield price in US$ tâ1, and VPC is the variable production costs (e.g., seeds, fertilizers, irrigation, human labor, power, etc.) in US$ haâ1 (Abdul Rahman et al., 2021). The IER concept (Devasenapathy, 2008) is defined as the land area required under monocropping to that under intercropping to obtain similar total income under a comparable agricultural management level. IER implements a comparable concept to LER; however, in opposition to LER, which measures crop productivity, instead, IER utilizes for gross income measurement. The IER was calculated as:IER=IERm+IERsIERm=YmiÃPm/YmsÃPmIERs=YsiÃPs/YssÃPs\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
